{"/service/ndnp/sdhi/batch_sdhi_grenada_ver01/data/sn99062034/00279523246/1907122801/0360.xml":{"full_text":"SELLING\nU S\nFOR 16 YEARS\nAboot Drugs and\nthe successful hand\nling of the Drug\nu s i n e s s a\nmoans a big advan\ntage to anyone who\ntrades with us. Re- _____\nmember this when yon\n\u00a9Ije giaiU? gcaCn\nMAOISOH, BOCVII ntXOVA.\nTELEPHONE, NO. 369.\nSATURDAY, DKCBMHEK 28, 1907\nTHE CITY.\nLOCAL NEWS.\nFresh cows wanted.\u2014W. R. Writer,\nwest side.\nMiss Nelle Tiurney of Winfred was\nin the city today.\nJoseph Oppernd and wife were mean\ning passengers for tsioux Falls.\nMiss Vera Beck was a morning pas\nsenger for Pipestone to spend Sunday.\nSouvenir post cards, new Carnegie\nlibrary, at The Daily Loader office.\nTake your photogragbs and pictures\nto Ireland for framing.\nDressmaking, corner Union avenue\nand Fifth street.\u2014Mrs. John Fintzel.\nWash ice delivered to any part of the\ncity.\u2014 Win. Kruger, phone free, farm\nline.\nIver Bradbury, cashier of the Dakota\nState Iwuik of Oldham was a visitor in\ntown today.\nWin. Hnntamer and C. F. Seid were\nhomecoming passengers this evening by\nthe Bouth train.\nJerry Lyons who has been visiting\nrelatives In the city departed thia even\ning foi Carthage.\nN. Sampson made the round trip to\nSionx Falls today in the interest of his\nrailroad grading contracts.\nT.J. Johnson and family returned\nthis evening from a Christmas visit\nwith relatives at Doon, Iowa.\nPeter Marquart, Goo. H. Waskey, C.\nE. Kennedy and E,B. Davis were even\ning passengers for Winfred to visit the\nI. O. O. F. lodge.\nLocal giain market: Wheat, No. 1,\n97 No. 2, 04 No. 8, 89 durum, 70 to\n73 flax, $1 oats, 40 corn, 48 barley,\n77 to 81.\nMrs. Alice Craney, matron of tht\nstate penitentiary at Sioux Falls, i.\nvisiting her parents, Dr. and Mrs. 8.M.\nJenks, in this city.\nIt is nice to have milk and cream on\nyour table that you can depend on be\ning pure, clean aud wholesome. Von\ncan get it by phoning the creamery\n188.\nEgan Express: The Misses Bertha\nLoncks and itfora Lynch who are at\ntending the Normal school at Madison\narrived home Saturday to spend the\nholiday vacation.\nHAS TAUGHT US\nMANY THINGS\nhave a proscription\nto be\nSCHUTZ KETCHAM\ndispe nsea\nWo got a double doso of No. 1\nFKKNCH SOFT S E\nWALL NUTS and rather than\nreturn them we are going to\nsell 200 pounds at\n15 Gents Per Pound\nNice to crack these long winter\nevenings. Order some now.\nThoy cannot last laat at this\nprice\nYours very truly\nH. J. MUNRO, the Grocer, Madison\nMrs. David Audiews. nee Zella Web\nster, of Seattle, Wash., was an arrival\nby the north train this morning and\nwas met at the depot by her friends,\nMisses Amanda Holle and Delia Sheri\ndan.\nRev. Dr. R. M. Hardman of Grace\nchurch was a morning passenger for\nSioux Falls where tomorrow he will\nconduct service in the cathedral in the\nabsence of Bishop Hare.\n\"The Little Prospector\" which\ncomes to Madison on Dec. 80 contains\nmany new ideas, situations and clim\naxes, and is by far the most entertain\ning and thrilling play of life in the\nmining camps of the Golden West ever\nwritten.\nSioux Falls Argus Leader: Harry\nSchales of Pipestone, but at one time\none of the popular mixologists of Sioux\nFalls, passed through the city Tuesday\nevening for Mitchell, where he and\nMrs. Schales spent Christmas with\ntheir daughter.\nNewly elected officers of Madison\nchapter. R. A. M., were installed last\nevening as follows: F. C. Smith,high\npriest C. A. Bergstreser, king J. LI.\nWilliamson, scribe F. R. VanSlyke,\nsecretary F. D. Fitts, treasurer: J. L.\nJones, captain of the hosts Win. Rae,\nprincipal sojourner, H. O. Curtis, royal\narch captain: D-McKinnon,John Blew\nitt,F. C. Metcalf, captains of the vails\nWm. Metcalf, tyler.\nE. J. Costello is in receipt of a letter\nfrom his former business partner, J. P.\nJensen, who recently went to Seattle,\nWash., with a view of locating. Mr.\nJensen reports a delightful climate,\nflowers in bloom and grass is green as\nin June in South Dakota, but he is not\npleased with the business outlook. He\nhas finally decided not to lcxate in\nSeattle but will visit other localities in\nsearch of a business location, and may\ndecide to return to Madison.\nGen. W. H. H. Beadle of Madison\nwill celeorate his seventieth birthday\non Jan. 1, 1908. On that day he will\ndeliver an address before the South Da\nkota Educational association at its\nmeeting at Watertown. The press of\nthe state, referring to clen. Beadle as\nthe father of education in South Dako\nta, is practically unanimous in urging\nsubstantial recognition of \"his great\nwork by the Educational association\nupon his appearance at Watertown.\nThe people of Madison where Gen.\nBeadle has resided many years will ap\npreciate* the honors which may be be\nstowed upon him,\nAberdeen American: The prelimi\nnary hearing of Jacob and Gustav\nHonegger for selling liquor to a min\nor WM kflM yesterday Mat*\nJones and they were bound over to the\nnext term of court in $00 bonds each.\nThe minor in the case was T. Do Witt\nTalmage Young, who was frozen to\ndeath while intoxicated a couple of\nweeks ago. Their hearing was post\nponed a few days\"ago*,to enable Uustav\nHonegger, of Sioux FalLs, to get here.\nThe witnesses yesterday were John\nPeterson, a bartender for the Honeg\ners, Chris Christiansen, the man who\nwas with Young on the fatal day and\nRev. Sanderson, who helped Christian\nson put Young into the buggy to leave\nthis city for Sand Lake.\ne\nam\nmt\nn\na\nIn the telegraphic news columns of\nThe Daily Leader last evening was con\ntained a report of the sentencing of\nper\nsons convicted of intent to commit\nfraud by using the mails in connection\nwith the sale of stock in the Lost Span\nish Bullion MineR company. The trial\nwas had at Denver, Col., and is of local\ninterest owing to the fact that W. B.\nCameron, one of those sentenced, was a\nfonner^resident of Madison. Follow\ning are those sentenced and the penalty\ninflicted: \"George S. Dubers and C.\nL. Blackwell, thirty days in jail and\n11,000 fine each William H. Wilson,\nW. B. Cameron, A.E. Keabler and Ar\nthur Lawrence, fifteen days' imprison\nment and $500 tine each Arthur Levan\nand E. W. Soblon. $100 fine and costs,\namounting to $200 K. C. Hunt and\nDanton Pinkus,#j0 fine and $150 costs.\nSTRANGE CHARACTER\nAdditional Particular! of the\nDeath of\nMrs.\nn\nSvendson at\nSioux City\nSionx City, Dec.27. \u2014While investiga\ntiot by the authorities yesterday served\nto throw considerable light on the life\nof Mrs, E. A. Longenback, which is\nbelieved to be the right name of the\nwoman of many aliases, whose charred\nhotly was found in her room in the Bol\nton block on Christmas day. the man\nner of her death remains a mystery-\nIt is the opinion of Coioner Roboins\nand the nolice that the woman's death\nwas due to an accident.\nThe fact that she bad told O. F.\nStetfen, who is in temporary charge of\nthe Bolton block, that she would like\nto have hi a assist her in drawing up a\nwill, and her remark to W. A. Smith,\nthe shoestring merchant, that she was\ntired of life, led many to favor\ntheory of suicide.\nNotwithstandnig that she had spent\nthe most of the past ten years in Sioux\nCity the woman had only a few ac\nquaintances here, among the most inti\nmate of whom was Police Matron\nThurston. That she has led an unhap\npy and mysterious existence ie evi\ndenced by letters which were found\namong the effects of her scantily fur\nnished apartments.\nLittle is known of the dead woman's\npast. She has a daughter, Mies Eliza\nbeth Longenback. in Boston. The\nmotler told Mrs. Thurston tnc daugh\nter was taKing a post graduate course\nin medicine there. She said she never\nheard tioni her daughter, anl did not\nknow her address, but that during tnc\npast year or to she bad sent her money\nand wearing apparel to the value of\nabout $2,000. She said tne goods wen\nsent to a financial agent in Boston, who\nforwarded them to the young woman.\nIt is known Mrs. Longenback was a\ngood patron of the dry goods stores\nThe daughter took a three-year course\nin the Sioux City College of Medicine\nand few years ago worked for a time\nin tne office of Dr. Miltcn Daily, po\nlice surgeon.\nAbout two yeaia ago Mrg. Longen\nback lived in Jackson street, Detween\nFourteenth and Fifteenth streets, and\nit is said phe then went under tht\nname of Mrs. Crawford. Sne uwd\nthat name also at Brookings. S. D..\nwhere she owned a farm.\nIn a packet of letters in a quilt were\nseveral whi'-h showed the woman has\npassed under at least five names. Com\numuications from Wentworth and\nMadison, S.D., in both of which places\nshe had resided for a short time, re\nferred to her as Mrs. C. K. Svendson\nA letter from Madison speaks of tin\nwriter's daughter coming to visit her.\nThe communication says a mysterious\nperson, referred to as M., has bwn\nhanging about the windows of her\nhome nights.\nIt is known that the woman lived for\nseveral weeks as Mrs. C. K. Sears. She\nrepresented herself at tnat time to be\nan herb doctor, and sold medicine that\nas recommended to care cancer.\nAbout a year ago she lived for seveial\nmonths in Lincoln.\nThe gruesome discovery of the wo\nman's body was made shortly after\nnoon by Mr. Steffen, who had gone to\nher room in answei to her request for\nassistance in drawing up a will. She\ncalled on Mr. Steffen last Saturday, and\noccupants of the block did not see her\nalive after that day.\nAt that time she gave as her reason\nfor wishing to make a will that she\nwas very ill and feared she had not\nlong to live.\nBeing very busy, Mi. Steffen delayed\nhis call until Chiistmas day. Receiv\ning no response to a knock on the door,\nhe secured a pass key and entered the\nroom. Clothing and hair burned away\nthe body was found lying on its back\nin oue corner of the room. There were\nno evidences thft the woman had\nstruggled in her death agonies. The\nfew furnishings of the room were in\nalmost perfect order,aud only that part\nof the ancarpeted floor on which lay\nthe body had come in contact with the\nflames. On the white suiface of the\nwall a few inches away were threw\nDlackened handprints, making it appar\nent that the woman had made a feeble\nattempt to rise while the flames were\nconsuming her.\nPartly concealed under one side of\nthe body was a small spirit lamp while\na large kerosene lamp stood a couple\nfeet away. A small night lamp rest\non a metal wash stand, and a tw\nburner coal oil stove, ured for cookin\nwas in the opposite corner of\nrootn. Neither lamp nor stove w\nlighted,and the bowl of the spirit lau\nwas empty. The furniture of\nroom consisted of a stand, curtai\nand a few dishes. There was\ncouch nor bed. For years the worn\nhad spent her nigbts in a rocki\nchair.\nOne theory in which little eredei\nis placed is ttoat the woman stood on\npile of paper and deliberately ignited\nwith the spirit lamp which was fou\nunder her body. Burned paper v\nfound in all parts of the room.\nBy Police Matron Thurston, w\ncalled on the woman on Friday, it\ntnought tnat her clothing may hs\ncaught fir* while she was combing I\nhair She nad long lahoied under I\nlelusion that there were cinders a\nbugs in her hair. With a lamp on\n1\nfloor beside her she would comb it\nhours at a time. Lately she had\npeatedly asked Mrs. Thurston to vi\nber. saying she was sick and wan\nsomeone to talk to ner.\nMrs. Longenback was a member\nthe Ladies of the Maccabees of\nWorld and of Banner lodge No. 28, !l\ngree of Honor, A. O. U. W., and\nried life insurance in the two orderi\nthe amount of $2,000 in the former\ncietv and $1,000 in the latter. 1\ndues were paid to October, 1908.\nCoroner Robbins does not think an\ninquest necessary, as he is of the opi\"\nion that death was due to an accident.\nThe Churches.\nPresbyterian church Subject of\nmorning discourse. How Old Art Thou?\nSunday school and Christian Endeavor\nat usual hours preaching at 7:i50 both\nmorning and evening services will par\ntake of New Year thoughts. All\" cor\ndially invited.\u2014 D. J. Mitterling, Pas\ntor.\nChristian Science\u2014Service at the\nresidence of C. W. Wood, Blanche ave\nnue and Eighth street, 10:45 a.m. snb\nject. Christian Science. An invitation\nextended.\nNorwegian Lutheran Church\u2014Ser\nvice in the morning at 10:80 Sunday\nhool at 12 o'clock Luther League at\n(5 no evening service. You are cor\ndially invited.\u2014M. K. Aaberg, Pastor.\nBaptist church\u2014Morning worship.\n10:80: sermon by the pastor, subject.\nGreeting the New Year with a cheer\nSunday school, 12, Frank C. Bulltr, su\nperintendent B. Y. P. U., fi:30. Miss\nOlive Shaw, leader evening service,\n:ii0 sermon, When Jesus comes to re\nward his servants. This is the last in\nthe series of sermons from popular gos\nospel sermons.\u2014Fred Everett Stockton,\nPastor.\nNo change of program at Dreamland\ntoday because of non arrival of new\nfilms. David Jenks will do specialty\nwork this evening, besides regular pro\ngram. Complete change Monday.\nTo Restore Life.\nIt is said that a prominent adantist\nhas discovered a method to restore life\nto animals and people appaiently dead\nby alternately pumping the gas out\nof the lungs and pumping oxygen in\nto produce artificial respiration. The\nest thing to put now life into an\nordinary tired, worn out individual is\nglass of golden grain belt beer. It\nis a wholesome nerve food and restores\nthe energy to weary body and brain\nOrder of your'nearest dealer.\nCured of Bright's Disease\nMr. Robert O. Burke, Elnora. N.Y\nwrites \"Before I started to use Foley's\nKidney Cure I had to get up from twel\nto fifteen times a night, and was all\nbloated up with dropsy and my eyesight\nwas so impaired 1 could hardly s\u00bbie one\nof my fatxnly across the room. I had\ngiven up ad hope of living, when a friend\nrecommended Foley's Kidney Cure.\nOne 50c bottle worked wonders and be\nfore I had taken the third bo